title: Keeping hidden state vector of RNN layers inside the model at online operation

labels.name: type:enhancement
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

body:
When running an onnx model that contains an RNN layer in real-time (i.e. frame by frame), we need to feed and receive the hidden state vector of the RNN explicitly at the inference with onnxruntime. An example inference can be seen in here: https://github.com/microsoft/AEC-Challenge/blob/a66686c0ed22bc757551edb16b40964068adeaa5/baseline/icassp2022/enhance.py#L85

It would be much better to cache the hidden state vector inside the model. So that, we can use the cached vector at each inference and update it at the end of the inference within the model. This way, we do not need to deal with the hassle of handling this vector. 

**Possible solution**
PyTorch solution: I have created a "nn.Parameter" in the model, where I am caching the RNN hidden state vector there and update it at every inference. This solution works perfectly in PyTorch.

When I export the PyTorch model to onnx and use it with onnxruntime in Python API, I noticed that the parameter in the model is not updated at each inference. Hence this solution does not work with onnxruntime.

I would appreciate any possible solution for this feature.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using): 1.10.0

**Describe the bug**
The same ONNX model gives different outputs when run in a python environment vs a javascript environment

**System information**

Javascript info
Running in browser with ORT pulled from `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/onnxruntime-web/dist/ort.min.js`

**To Reproduce**
I am trying to deploy a GAN model in browser. Currently I am using a toy model that generates `8x8x4` PNG images. The model takes as input a vector of size `(256,)` sampled from a random normal distribution. The model should give the exact same output for a specific input vector. Between runtimes (python, javascript), the output might not be identical, but it should be similar. Currently, python and javascript runtimes are giving completely different results.

Python setup:

```python
layers = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(dim, dim*2),
            nn.Dropout(p=0.3),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(dim*2, dim*2),
            nn.Dropout(p=0.3),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(dim*2, dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(dim, dim)
        )

class InferenceModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, layers):
        super().__init__()
        self.layers = layers
        
    def forward(self, input):
        input = input.unsqueeze(0) # convert (256,) to (1,256)
        # model generates an output of float values
        # these floats are clamped to 0,1, multiplied by 255 and converted to Longs
        output = (self.layers(input).clamp(0,1) * 255).type(torch.LongTensor)
        # output is a vector, we reshape to an image
        output = output.view((8,8,4))
        return output

im = InferenceModel(layers)
im.eval() # eval called before onnx trace
im.cpu()

dummy_input = torch.randn((256)
torch.onnx.export(im, args=dummy_input, f='model.onnx', verbose=True, input_names=['input'], output_names=['output'])
```

Python / JS runtimes

Rather than clutter things here, I've attached a zip file with the ONNX model and testing code for both python and javascript

[onnx_example.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/8403643/onnx_example.zip)

```

- main.html - html for javascript testing
- model.onnx - onnx model file
- onnx_test.py - code to test onnx model in python
- python_output.npy - python output in npy format (np.save)
- script.js - javascript snippet for generating an output and saving it to a json file
```

You will notice in `onnx_test.py` and `script.js`, the input vector to the model is hard coded to be the exact same input.

You can see the output arrays in `js_output.json` and `python_output.npy` are significantly different.

Expected greater correspondence between output arrays in python / javascript runtime for the same input vector

title: Performance reduction due to copying of output OrtValues to numpy arrays
body:
I tested hand-made multiple input/output onnx-model and observed that performance is reduced by copying of OrtValues to numpy arrays if InferenceSession "run" method is used. I used TVM EP but the issue is not depends on any type of execution provider.
My view is that it is excess copying which can be skipped in some usual cases.
I considered two approaches: 1. Construct numpy arrays after inference based on memory allocated for output ORT tensors (`PyArray_SimpleNewFromData` can be used instead of `PyArray_SimpleNew`). 2. Create numpy arrays with fixed output shapes before inference and construct output ORT tensors based on memory preallocated in the numpy arrays.

The first approach requires small changings in current code. But it leads to potential problem related to memory ownership. if InferenceSession was released when its output ORT tensors are released too and numpy array will link to spoiled memory. It should be noted the approach does not work for sparse tensors, the copying is still needed.
I have questions to community: Can I and how to manage memory ownership for OrtValue and OrtTensor? And how safe is this management?

The second approach solves the ownership problem, but has own issues. It works (I checked it) for onnx-model with fixed architecture (all shapes are known). Obviously it does not work for dynamic onnx-model where some tensor shapes, particularly output tenors shapes, depends on input tensor data. In the latter case the current approach with copying should be used. The most common case in practice is dynamic onnx-models where some dimensions of shape are unknown (e.g. batch size). From one hand for this case the output shapes are not known before inference, but they are needed for correct memory allocation by numpy arrays. From other hand input shapes are known before inference and if we have shape inference mechanism, we can get output shapes. Other issue is InferenceSession "run" method returns list of python objects in general case, not numpy arrays only. It means we should know python objects types before inference. I'm not sure but it looks like types from outputs from InferenceSession::GetModelOutputs can be used for it.
I have questions to community: The main one is can output shapes be calculated for given input shapes in ORT? Particularly do ORT have shape inference method? I found Graph::UpdateShapeInference(node), but it does not change outputs from InferenceSession::GetModelOutputs although they are binded to graph outputs. Can we used outputs from InferenceSession::GetModelOutputs to check types and construct correct vector of python objects before inference?

**Urgency**
There is no special deadlines

**System information**
There is no special system requirements. I performed tests on Linux (Ubuntu 18.04) using ONNX runtime python API

**To Reproduce**
To observe the performance reduction any onnx-model can be used, but the effect is more highlighted in case of multiple output onnx-models. To evaluate performance reduction for specific model it is enough to measure time of [the circle](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/onnxruntime_pybind_state.cc#L1427) execution (by std::chrono for example) and compare with full inference performance.

title: directly use memory mapped data for external data initializers (and e…
body:
**Description**: 

Directly use memory mapped data for external data initializers. 

**Motivation and Context**
- **Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?**

Creating sessions for models with external data initializers incurs a significant penalty in releases after 1.7. While the data for these initializers is memory mapped during load it is subsequently copied during creation of their corresponding tensors. With this update the memory mapped data is used directly and external data initializers are excluded from memory planning to avoid any allocation of additional space.

Sample test results using the citrinet model referenced in issue [10977](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/10977) are shown below. 

The `VmPeak`, `VmHWM` and `VmRSS` are captured from `/proc/self/status` immediately after model load and before program exit. Model load time and peak memory are improved significantly. Processing time for the first inference incurs a small penalty as memory mapped regions are faulted in but is comparable afterwards.

Testing with `valgrind` reports no errors and no leaks.

**Description**:

This has been clarified that this is indeed not the case (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/11107#issuecomment-1090656720). title: Re-implment the function support in onnxruntime
body:
**Description**: Currently the implementation of function support in onnxruntime is quite confusion. There are some history reasons. The initial implementation of "Function" was introduced to onnxruntime before the "Function" concept introduce to onnx, originally it is just for the fusion. Later, people try to leverage the same code to handle the functions in onnx. Since we have more and more trick cases in onnx function, the implementation become very mess. This PR is to re-implement the function support and make it clearer.

Today there are three cases you will have function introduced:
1. an onnx operator that has function body
2. a model local function
3. a function created by onnxruntime (for fusion)
(#3 will be deprecated soon, please refer to PR #10632)

Today, ONNX function doesn't support recursive. Therefore, in ONNXRuntime, we don't need to introduce the "Function Call" convention, we just have two ways to run the function: use an optimized kernel for the whole function, or inline the function. Based on this assumption, the design is:

1. during model loading phase, load all the model local function, generated a schema for those local functions and make sure it has a type/shape inference function attached.  
2. When a node in ORT graph refer to a local function, refer it to the generated schema in the model.
3. Please note that onnx "function" is not a real function in programming language, it is more like a "function template" that haven't instantiated yet. In model loading phase, we only need to validate the graph and resolve type/shapes, there is no need to instantiate the function body.
4. During graph partition, if there is no optimized kernel assigned to the function node, instantiate the function body on the node, then inline it to the main graph.

This PR will fix issue: #10250 

There are still some codes may need further PRs to clean up.

title: Move OrtValueVector from onnxruntime-training to onnxruntime
body:
**Description**:

Python binding of onnxruntime-training disables the implicit conversion of std::vector<OrtValue> into a list of OrtValue but instead returns a OrtValueVector. Disabling this mecanism is [twice faster](https://github.com/sdpython/cpyquickhelper/blob/master/_doc/notebooks/cbenchmark_vector.ipynb). The proposal is to unify both API and returns an OrtValueVector everytime onnxruntime or onnxruntime-training returns a list of OrtValue.

Second item which I leave open for discussion: should we also enable the implementation of DLPack protocol in onnxruntime and not only in onnxruntime-training? Since November last year, numpy implements [DLPack protocol](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/19083). It was introduced in [0.22](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/release/1.22.0-notes.html).

**Motivation and Context**

This change makes the API more consistent accross onnxruntime and onnxruntime-training and improves functions returning list of OrtValue.

It addesses one [comment](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9610#discussion_r839829390) and its [reply](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9610#issuecomment-1085780291).

title: Set up ONNX integration weekly pipeline to run ORT training CI with latest ONNX
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
To set up ONNX integration weekly pipeline to run ORT training CI with latest ONNX

**Motivation and Context**
Today ONNX integration is usually initiated during ONNX release. Most of the integration work is completed after ONNX release. The release manager (usually an ONNX contributor) follows ONNX release instruction and understands from the instruction that there is a need to update ORT with ONNX release. The release manager informs the ORT team (creating an issue in ORT repo) the work needs to be done. The amount of work in ORT varies. It depends on how many new and updated ops there are in the current ONNX release, how much changes to the API and shape inference functionalities. It also depends on if there is any ONNX issue encountered during ORT integration. In this case, ORT shall give feedback to the ONNX team to fix any ONNX issue, hopefully before the ONNX release, and continue the integration.

Often much of ONNX integration work is done after ONNX release, there is a risk that ONNX is released with issues that can only get detected during ONNX integration. In such cases we may need to release an ONNX patch which is sub-optimal.
This PR is to reduce the unpredictability of ONNX and ORT release schedule and to avoid any risk of releasing ONNX with undetected bugs.

A CI pipeline is created: 
https://dev.azure.com/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/_build?definitionId=191

It runs weekly with ONNX main branch. When there is a breaking API change or a shape inference change in ONNX repo that requires extra work from ORT, the pipeline run will let us know to take appropriate steps.

title: Option to build with DML as an external project
body:
**Description**: Adds a third way to build ORT+DML by making the (private) DirectML repo an external project.

There are now three ways to consume DirectML in this repo:

1) **Public** = the build points at a pre-built copy of DirectML distributed as a NuGet package. This is the default.

2) **Custom** = the build points at a local DML installation (bin/, include/, lib/). This is useful for anyone (not just DML devs) that wants to build with a prebuilt DirectML that isn't distributed as a NuGet (e.g. GDK builds and internal WindowsAI build).
    - If using CMake directly you set `-Donnxruntime_USE_CUSTOM_DIRECTML=ON`
    - If using build.py you set `--dml_path <install_dir>`.

3) **Private** = the build points at the DirectML source repo and builds it as part of the main project. This is useful for CI purposes and sharing a common git version in the WindowsAI staging branch.
    - If using CMake directly you set `-Donnxruntime_USE_CUSTOM_DIRECTML=ON -Ddml_EXTERNAL_PROJECT=ON`
    - If using build.py you set `--dml_external_project`.
    - Change the source version by modifying the `GIT_TAG <sha>` in dml.cmake.

Build Type | onnxruntime_USE_CUSTOM_DIRECTML | dml_EXTERNAL_PROJECT
-----------|---------------------------------|---------------------
Public     | OFF                             | OFF
Custom     | ON                              | OFF
Private   | ON                              | ON

The "Public" build type is the default, and any mainline branches (e.g. master, rel-*) subject to CI
should use the public build configuration. Topic branches can use the internal build type for testing,
but they must be buildable with a public NuGet package before merging with a mainline branch.

title: [CUDA] Rollback TileMemcpy and TileBatchedMemcpy when Block Size is Small
body:
For TileMemcy and TileBatchedMemcy CUDA kernel, #11053 changed to launch threads from inputs instead of outputs. This causes regression when input size is small, because the block number from input size is too small to fill all streaming multiprocessors. This PR will use the block size to determine whether we launch threads from inputs or outputs.

With this change, the perf for some customer models come back to previous level. More tests using different input sizes also show that when the block number is larger enough, we can have the perf gain when launching the threads from inputs.
